{\bf intro}

Let \mengi{\xi^{n}} be a $\delta_{0}$-Poisson-Dirichlet$(\alpha,0)$-coalescent with transition rates 
\begin{equation}
  \label{eq:1}
  \begin{split}
   & 1 +  \frac{2^{1-\kappa}}{\kappa - 1 } <   m_{\infty}  <  1 +  \frac 1{\kappa - 1} \\
    C_{\kappa} & =  \frac{2}{m_{\infty}^{2}}\svigi{  \one{\kappa = 2}   +  \one{\kappa > 2}  \frac{c_{\kappa}}{ 2^{\kappa}\svigi{\kappa - 2}\svigi{\kappa - 1}}} \\
  p_{n;k_{1},\ldots, k_{r};s} & =  \frac{\alpha^{r+s-1}\svigi{r+s-1}! }{(n-1)! }\prod_{i=1}^{r}\svigi{k_{i} - 1 - \alpha}_{k_{i} - 1} \\
 \lambda_{n;k_{1},\ldots, k_{r};s} & =  \frac{C_{\kappa}}{C_{\kappa} + c(1-\alpha) }\one{r=1,k_{1}=1} +  \frac{c}{C_{\kappa} + c(1-\alpha)}  p_{n;k_{1},\ldots, k_{r};s} 
\end{split}
\end{equation}
where $k_{i} \in \mengi{2,3,\ldots, n}$ and $2 \le \sum_{i}k_{i}\le n$
and $s = n - \sum_{i}k_{i}$ and $\kappa + 2 < c_{\kappa} < \kappa^{2}$
for $\kappa > 2$ and $0<\alpha < 1$. The
$\delta_{0}$-Poisson-Dirichlet$(\alpha,0)$-coalescent is an example of
a $\Xi$-coalescent where simultaneous mergers of a random number of
ancestral lineages (blocks of the current partition) may occur at such
times.


Here we consider the time-changed continuous-time
$\delta_{0}$-Poisson-Dirichlet$(\alpha,0)$-coalescent with
time-change function $G(t) = \int_{0}^{t}1/v(s){\rm d}s $ where   $v(t)
= \lim_{N\to \infty}N_{\lfloor t/c_{N} \rfloor}/N$  and $N_{r}$ is the
population size $r$ generations into the past.      Given that
$\mengi{\xi^{n}}$ reached $m$ blocks at time $\tau$ then the waiting
time until the next merger is
\begin{displaymath}
\prb{T > t : \tau } =  e^{- \lambda_{m} \svigi{G(t+\tau) - G(\tau)} }
\end{displaymath}
where $\lambda_{m}$ is the total coalescent rate when $m$ blocks.  
Then, assuming $G$ is invertible, it holds that
\begin{displaymath}
t = G^{-1}\svigi{ G(\tau) -   \frac{1}{\lambda_{m}} \log(1-U) } - \tau
\end{displaymath}
using that $U =  1 -  e^{-\lambda_{m} \svigi{G(t+\tau) - G(\tau)} } $
where $U$ is a standard random uniform on $(0,1)$.


Population decline  (reduction in population size forward-in-time) can
be taken such that   $N_{t} = Ne^{\rho t}$   where $N_{t}$ is the
population size at time $t$ into the past.  
 Set $v : s \mapsto e^{\rho s}$ for $s\in (0,\infty)$, and $\rho >
 0$ fixed.   Then  $G(t) = \int_{0}^{t}e^{-\rho s}{\rm d}s = \svigi{1
 - e^{-\rho t}}/\rho$ ($\rho > 0$) and
 \begin{equation}
 \label{eq:2} 
 t =  \frac 1{\rho}\log \svigi{e^{-\rho \tau} -  \frac{\rho}{\lambda_{m}}\log(1-U) } + \tau 
\end{equation}



Population growth (increase in population size forward-in-time) can be
taken such that  $N_{t} = Ne^{-\rho t}$.  Set $v:s \mapsto e^{-\rho s}$
for $s\in (0,\infty)$, $\rho > 0$ fixed.  Then $G(t) = \svigi{e^{\rho
t} - 1}/\rho$,  and
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:3}
t =  \frac 1{\rho} \log \svigi{1 - e^{-\rho \tau} \frac {\rho} {\lambda_{m}} \log(1-U)  }
\end{equation}




